<P>
IMF Approves $1.4 Billion for Argentina: Argentina received approval for a 
$1.4-billion loan from the International Monetary Fund. An IMF spokesman said 
the lending agency's executive board approved the so-called standby 
arrangement, which allows the country to draw down the funds over the next 16 
months. The approval showed that the IMF was satisfied that Argentina had begun 
the process of economic reform that lenders felt was critically needed before 
new funds could be provided. Argentina has made virtually no payments on its 
$60 billion in foreign debt, piling up about $4.4 billion in interest payment 
arrears, according to some estimates. 
</P>
