<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 2; Column 2; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
170 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: GARDEN GROVE; 
</P>
<P>
COUNCIL TO CONSIDER PROPOSAL FOR HOTEL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Plans by La Quinta Motor Inns to construct a 168-unit, three-story hotel in 
Garden Grove will be considered tonight when the City Council meets. 
</P>
<P>
The $8-million project, planned for a 2.8-acre site at the northwest corner of 
Haster Street and Garden Grove Boulevard, has been delayed while the city and 
the San Antonio-based developer wrangle over issues raised by the proposed 
hotel's location in the Santa Ana River flood plain. 
</P>
<P>
Under guidelines issued by the Federal Emergency Management Agency, the project 
would have to be elevated five feet to protect it in the event of a flood of a 
severity to be expected once in 100 years. 
</P>
<P>
On Oct. 23, city officials determined that La Quinta was in default of its 
agreement with the city for failing to submit completed plans, including the 
five-foot elevation, by Aug. 30. All the parties are scheduled to try to 
resolve the issue tonight, which could result in a time extension or the 
cancellation of the agreement with La Quinta. 
</P>
<P>
The meeting is scheduled for 7:30 p.m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
HOTELS -- ORANGE COUNTY; GARDEN GROVE (CA) -- DEVELOPMENT AND REDEVELOPMENT 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA111389-0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 134581 </DOCID>
